Tutorial for PALM

Zhoujingpeng Wei1*

1Department of Biostatistics and Medical Informatics, University of Wisconsin-Madison

*zwei74@wisc.edu

2025-11-06

Package

PALM 0.1.0

1 Introduction

This R package implements PALM [1], a quasi-Poisson-based framework for robust, scalable, and reproducible identification of covariate-associated microbial features in large-scale microbiome association studies and meta-analyses. The package supports both single-study association analysis and meta-analysis across multiple studies. This tutorial provides examples illustrating how to perform meta-analysis using PALM.

Figure 1 presents a schematic overview of the PALM framework for meta-analysis. For each study, PALM takes as input the relative-abundance (RA) count data of microbial features, sequencing depth, the covariate of interest, and any confounders to be adjusted for, and generates absolute-abundance (AA)level summary statistics. Specifically, for each feature, PALM first fits a quasi-Poisson null model (excluding the covariate of interest), then computes score statistics based on the null model output and the covariate, and finally constructs RA-level summary statistics (i.e., RA association effect estimates and variances) from the score statistics. Next, PALM corrects for compositional effects using the RA-level summary statistics across all features to derive AA-level summary statistics. The forest plot illustrates the AA-level summary statistics for an example feature. These summary statistics are then combined across studies via meta-analysis to obtain the overall effect estimate, variance, and p-value. Covariate-associated microbial features are identified based on the resulting p-values, with multiple-testing correction applied across features.

Figure 1: Schematic overview of PALM for meta-analysis

3 Meta-analysis given all samples of all participating studies

There are two approaches PALM can run meta-analysis.

Approach #1: When individual-level sample data from all participating studies are available, the function palm can directly take these data as input to generate, harmonize, and combine summary association statistics across studies, enabling fast and reliable identification of covariate-associated microbial features.

Approach #2: When individual-level data are not centrally available, summary statistics can be generated separately for each study using the functions palm.null.model and palm.get.summary. These summary statistics can then be transferred to a central location and combined for feature-level meta-analysis using the function palm.meta.summary.

We demonstrate Approach #1 in this session and Approach #2 in the next session.

Here, we use datasets from two metagenomic studies of colorectal cancer (CRC) [2] to demonstrate the usage of each function. CRC_abd is a list of sample-by-feature matrices containing the relative abundance counts of 267 species under the order Clostridiales from the two studies. CRC_meta is a data frame containing sample-level metadata from the same studies, including the following variables:

  • Sample identity: Sample_ID

  • Study name: Study

  • Disease status: Group

## Load CRC data
data("CRC_data")
CRC_abd <- CRC_data$CRC_abd
CRC_meta <- CRC_data$CRC_meta
# Prepare input data
rel.abd <- list()
covariate.interest <- list()
for(d in unique(CRC_meta$Study)){
  rel.abd[[d]] <- CRC_abd[CRC_meta$Sample_ID[CRC_meta$Study == d],]
  disease <- as.numeric(CRC_meta$Group[CRC_meta$Study == d] == "CRC")
  names(disease) <- CRC_meta$Sample_ID[CRC_meta$Study == d]
  covariate.interest[[d]] <- matrix(disease, ncol = 1, dimnames = list(names(disease), "disease"))
}

# palm analysis
meta.result <- PALM::palm(rel.abd = rel.abd, covariate.interest = covariate.interest, prev.filter = 0)
# Caption
caption_html <- tags$p(
  tags$strong("Table 1. Summary of meta-analysis results for the top 20 microbial features."),
  "The table displays, for each microbial feature, the overall association effect estimate, standard error, p-value, and q-value for testing the overall effect; the p-value and q-value for assessing cross-study heterogeneity; and the study-specific summary statistics (effect estimates and standard errors) from individual studies. All numerical values are rounded to four decimal places."
)

# Generate table
tbl <- meta.result$disease %>%
  dplyr::slice(1:20) %>%
  dplyr::mutate(across(where(is.numeric), ~ round(.x, digits = 4))) %>%
  datatable()

# Display caption + table

Figure 3: Study-specific PALM effect estimates and cross-study consistency
The figure displays study-level association effect estimates (dots) with corresponding 95% confidence intervals (lines) for each microbial feature. Yellow-shaded rows mark features with evidence of cross-study heterogeneity (q-value 0.1). The overall consistency of PALM effect estimates across studies, together with the homogeneity q-values, demonstrates the robustness of the method.

4 Meta-analysis given samples of one study at a time

If the datasets of different studies live in different locations and cannot be conveniently shared among studies, we can first generate summary statistics for each study:

## Generate summary statistics for each study
null.obj.FR <- palm.null.model(rel.abd = rel.abd$`FR-CRC`, prev.filter = 0)
summary.stats.FR <- palm.get.summary(null.obj = null.obj.FR, covariate.interest = covariate.interest$`FR-CRC`)

null.obj.DE <- palm.null.model(rel.abd = rel.abd$`DE-CRC`, prev.filter = 0)
summary.stats.DE <- palm.get.summary(null.obj = null.obj.DE, covariate.interest = covariate.interest$`DE-CRC`)

These summary statistics can be transported to a central location for meta-analysis:

## Concatenate summary statistics
summary.stats.merge <- c(summary.stats.FR, summary.stats.DE)
names(summary.stats.merge) <- c("FR-CRC", "DE-CRC")

## Meta-analysis to harmonize and combine summary statistics across studies
meta.result.2 <- palm.meta.summary(summary.stats = summary.stats.merge)

The meta-analysis results generated in this way are identical to those from the previous session.

5 Meta-analysis of association scan for multiple covariates of interest

Microbiome association studies can involve a large number of covariates of interest (e.g., omics variables). We show here how to use PALM to meta-analyze eight microbiome-metabolome association studies [3]. In these eight studies, we have 101 genera and 450 metabolites and we are interested in identifying genera that are associated with individual metabolites. This analysis takes approximately 49 seconds.

## Load metabolite data: 
## You may see the following website on how to directly load data from 
## github into R https://github.com/ZjpWei/PALM/raw/main/Metabolite.rda
options(timeout = 300)
load(file = url("https://github.com/ZjpWei/PALM/raw/main/Metabolite.rda"))

## Change genera names
for(d in names(otu_data_lst)){
  colnames(otu_data_lst[[d]]) <-  gsub(".*;g__", "", colnames(otu_data_lst[[d]]))
}

## Get null model
null.obj <- palm.null.model(rel.abd = otu_data_lst, covariate.adjust = covariates_adjust_lst)

## Get summary statistics
summary.stat <- palm.get.summary(null.obj = null.obj, covariate.interest = cmpd_data_lst,
                                 cluster = cluster_data_lst)

## Meta-analysis
meta.scan.result <- palm.meta.summary(summary.stats = summary.stat)
# Caption
caption_html <- tags$p(
  tags$strong("Table 2. Summary of meta-analysis results for the top 20 microbial features across five metabolites."),
  "The table presents, for each microbial feature, the overall association effect estimate, standard error, p-value, and q-value for testing the overall effect; the p-value and q-value for assessing cross-study heterogeneity; and the study-specific summary statistics (effect estimates and standard errors) from individual studies. All numerical values are rounded to four decimal places."
)

meta.sum <- lapply(meta.scan.result, function(d){d %>% tibble::column_to_rownames("feature")})
selected.num <- sort(unlist(lapply(meta.sum, function(d){sum(d$qval <= 0.05)})), decreasing = TRUE)
top.cov.name <- names(selected.num)[1:min(5, length(selected.num))]
coef_mat <- do.call(cbind, lapply(meta.sum[top.cov.name], function(d){d[,"coef",drop=FALSE]}))
colnames(coef_mat) <- top.cov.name

# Generate table
tbl <- coef_mat %>% dplyr::slice(1:20) %>% 
  mutate(across(where(is.numeric), ~ round(.x, digits = 4))) %>% 
  datatable()

# Display caption + table
tagList(caption_html, tbl)
